374365d6-0855-4011-b3b7-c45c30af363a.10c9f60c-5db8-4974-8476-9e4fc94b11b1.description=
Checks if a number or word is greater than another number or word. Word comparison is case-sensitive in alphabetical order.

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
value1 > value2

Responses\:
success - The boolean operation was evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.
374365d6-0855-4011-b3b7-c45c30af363a.46c62bfa-62ac-4f0b-b2d1-cd40cf003db2.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-yyyy HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2
D	Day in year				Number		189
d	Day in month				Number		10
F	Day of week in month			Number		2
E	Day name in week			Text		Tuesday; Tue
u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0
k	Hour in day (1-24)			Number		24
K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12
m	Minute in hour				Number		30
s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z	Time zone				RFC 822 time zone	-800
X	Time zone				ISO 8601 time zone	-08; -0800; -08\:00
Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry
2001.07.04 AD at 12\:08\:56 PDT	yyyy.MM.dd G 'at' HH\:mm\:ss z		en		US
Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235+0700	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSZ	en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235-07\:00	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX	en		US
1309781336			unix			-		-

374365d6-0855-4011-b3b7-c45c30af363a.7d0e3e00-82db-4c76-8f35-683f9f2a2fca.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
374365d6-0855-4011-b3b7-c45c30af363a.b2a7d0e2-b177-4c64-9acb-46b8fe19d835.description=<pre> This operation runs a SQL SELECT query. The first row is returned on the first run of the operation. Subsequent calls with the same information will return the other rows. Inputs\: DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of the database server. DbType - The type of database to connect to. Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2, PostgreSQL and Custom. Default value\: Oracle Username - The username to use when connecting to the server. Password - The password to use when connecting to the server. instance - The name instance of MSSQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance. Example\: MSSQLSERVER DbPort - The port to connect to. Valid values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000, PostgreSQL\: 5432. Database - The name of the database to connect to. authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL) default value\: sql dbClass - The class name of the JDBC driver to use. dbURL - The URL required to load up the driver and make your connection. Command - The SQL query to execute. Delimiter - The delimiter to use between resulted values in "returnResult" and column names in "columnNames". Key - The key to help keep multiple query results distinct. timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. When the default value is used, there is no limit on the amount of time allowed for a running command to complete. Default values\: 0 databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. For more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description. Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true resultSetType - the result set type. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE. Default value\: TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE except DB2 which is overridden to TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY resultSetConcurrency - the result set concurrency. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY, CONCUR_UPDATABLE Default value\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY ignoreCase - If set to true the inputs' letters case will be ignored and converted to lowercase. Valid values\: true, false Default value\: true Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the data of one row, separated by the "Delimiter". columnNames - The names of all the columns returned, separated by the "Delimiter". rowsLeft - The number of remaining rows that match the query. Responses\: more items - More rows are available for retrieval. no more items - No more rows are available. failure - Failed to execute the command. Notes\: 1. SQL statement other than SELECT statement (like INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE) is not supported. In case statements other than SELECT are executed then the operation will fail but the statements might get partially or fully executed in the database. 2. If the column type is "ntext", the "returnResult" returns the name of the JDBC driver instead of the actual column value. In this case, use the "SQL Query LOB" operation instead. 3. Use the 'Command' input with caution as it can expose the target system to security risks. By exposing the 'Command' input as a prompt to the user, it will enable the user to execute any SQL command on the target system taking into account the permissions of the credentials given as inputs. Note\: Check the JDBC folder description for details on how to load database connectors. </pre> 374365d6-0855-4011-b3b7-c45c30af363a.cbed4f95-7b4d-4014-aa0f-c3307ed03ff3.description=
